content_chunks.content: This e-course on Built Environment Sustainability and Building Carbon Footprint, explores the built environment's impact on climate change, emphasizing carbon emissions in construction and renovation. Participants will learn about environmental regulations, carbon footprint calculations, and data's role in emissions understanding. Key topics include lifecycle assessment, the differences between new and renovated buildings, and strategies for reducing carbon footprints. The course also addresses circular renovation concepts and sustainability in public procurements and architectural competitions, offering a blend of theoretical insights and practical case studies and examples. It is designed for students, professionals, and anyone interested in sustainable building practices.

Carbon footprint technology for sustainable building design - this course delivers comprehensive methodologies for evaluating and reducing building environmental impact through advanced carbon assessment techniques. Technology for carbon management includes carbon footprint methodologies for precise emission calculation and lifecycle assessment frameworks for comprehensive environmental impact analysis. The course introduces new building carbon analysis techniques and renovated building carbon evaluation methods for comparing construction versus renovation scenarios. Participants gain expertise in environmental regulations compliance and sustainability standards implementation for regulatory adherence and best practice adoption. The curriculum covers circular renovation concepts for material reuse, Product Environmental Declarations (EPD) utilization, and BIM sustainability applications for integrated carbon management. Students develop skills in carbon emission calculations, climate change impact assessment, and carbon reduction strategies for sustainable building practices. The course prepares professionals to implement sustainable architectural competition guidelines, evaluate public procurement sustainability criteria, and leverage BIM technologies for carbon optimization across building lifecycles while addressing broader sustainability considerations beyond carbon emissions.

content_chunks.title: Introduction to Built Environment and Climate Change
Public Sector Building Projects and Product EPDs
